INTRODUCTION

Bathing or swimming in bodies of water that have significant e. coli levels pose a health risk. E. coli is often tested with a biological assay that can take some time to yield results. To get advance warning of risks of high e. coli levels more quickly, alternative chemical tests that can yield results faster can be used to predict high e. coli levels. This project aims to use data from the UK Environment Agency to search for correlations between the e. coli concentration and the results of various determinands, using data from 2013-2017.

THE DATA

The key fields included in this data set are the time of each sample, the location the sample was taken from, the material type, the type of test conducted (determinand), and the result of the test. This allows for plotting of various test results against factors like time, location, e. coli concentration, or biochemical oxygen demand, with the possibility of grouping these results by material type.

One of the limitations of this dataset is that it cant make statistically significant observations of how the climate around the UK is changing year after year, since only 5 years worth of samples are selected. Since the raw data for 5 years already has a file size of 3.3 GB, it would be a significant challenge to compile many more years worth of data to get to a point where a stiatistically significant trend could be observed.

Due to the sheer file size of the dataset, 3.3 GB, it had to be filtered down to include only observations of interest (the different filters applied are discussed in the next section, Preliminary Explorations). After applying a filter, the remaining observations had to be spread and then aggregated by sample time, location, and material type to be able to get to a tidy format. The wrangling process is performed on a sample data set to demonstrate the process.

PRELIMINARY EXPLORATIONS

Its difficult to compare each of the 70 different material types and each of the 1820 different tests performed, so the scope of analysis had to be narrowed down. The first approach was to filter for only the most common material types and determinands, in the hopes of revealing trends in how each determinand changed over time by clustering the data by material type. This proved to be an ineffective selection method, because each material type was tested for some determinands much more often than others, and some determinands were barely tested at all for some material types, making it difficult to compare them. An example of this was the comparison between seawater and sewage effluent. Though salinity was one of the most common determinands, it was far more frequently tested on seawater and barely tested at all on sewage effluent. This made a comparison between them based on salinity meaningless. Though this approach didnt lead to any model for relating material types to each other, this preliminary exploration revealed an important structure of the dataset. This allowed for a more informed and meaningful filtering of the raw data for the next hypotheses.

The next hypothesis was to predict e. coli concentrations based on results of chemical testing, so the five material types that were tested most frequently for e. coli were selected from the raw data set. By comparing the most common determinands to e. coli concentrations some significant relationships were identified.

A correlation table was first generated of each determinands relationship to e. coli concentration, shown below.

A correlation table gives a quick picture of whether there are correlations between any of the determinands and e. coli concentration. The table below shows that a linear model may not be the most effective predictive model. For that reason, each determinand is plotted against e. coli in section 2.

cor.ecoli <- NULL
for(i in 5:length(water.raw.ecoli)){
  assign(x = paste("x", i, sep = "-"), value = cor(x = water.raw.ecoli[i], y = water.raw.ecoli$E.coli.C.MF.no.100ml, use = "complete.obs"))
  cor.ecoli <- rbind(cor.ecoli, get(paste("x", i, sep = "-")))
}
row.names(cor.ecoli) <- colnames(water.raw.ecoli[,5:length(water.raw.ecoli)])
cor.ecoli

The low correlation values suggested that not many relationships would fit a linear model well and that each determinand needed to be plotted against e. coli individually to identify any patterns. The plots of the most significant relationships are shown below.

E. coli vs.Water Temperature

## [1] "Positively-skewed normal distribution"
ggplot(water.raw.ecoli, aes(x = `Temp.Water.cel`, y = `E.coli.C.MF.no.100ml`, color = E.coli.C.MF.conform)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.2)

E. coli vs.pH

## [1] "Negative-skewed normal distribution"
ggplot(water.raw.ecoli, aes(x = `pH.phunits`, y = `E.coli.C.MF.no.100ml`, color = E.coli.C.MF.conform)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.2)

E. coli vs.Nitrate.N

Slight exponential relationship, with more occurances of high e. coli concentrations at low concentration of Nitrate.N.

ggplot(water.raw.ecoli, aes(x = `Nitrate.N.mg.l`, y = `E.coli.C.MF.no.100ml`, color = E.coli.C.MF.conform)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.2)

E. coli vs.Nitrite.N

Slight exponential relationship.

ggplot(water.raw.ecoli, aes(x = `Nitrite.N.mg.l`, y = `E.coli.C.MF.no.100ml`, color = E.coli.C.MF.conform)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.2)

E. coli vs.Dissolved Oxygen

Higher number of occurances of high e.coli at low oxygen dissolved amounts.

ggplot(water.raw.ecoli, aes(x = `Oxygen.Diss.mg.l`, y = `E.coli.C.MF.no.100ml`, color = E.coli.C.MF.conform)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.2)

Strong exponential relationship.

Exponential relationship.

ggplot(water.raw.ecoli, aes(x = `Sld.Sus.105C.mg.l`, y = `E.coli.C.MF.no.100ml`, color = E.coli.C.MF.conform)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.2)

CONCLUSION

There are noticeable patterns when each determinand is plotted against e. coli concentration, whether it be something of a normal distribution or an exponential relationship, so the next step is to split each determinands results into two categories, one in which the correspond e. coli concentration is above the regulatory standard of 900 cfu/100mL. This will be used to develop a predictive model that can give a probability that e. coli concentrations will be above safe levels, based on given chemical test results. Ultimately, this has the potential to give bathers earlier warning of high e. coli levels in water to prevent e. coli infections.
